Lucien<br>
&lt;&lt;. . .It seems that perpetrators of violence, especially those who would not do violence to another under normal circumstances but who are forced or decide to do so in war always suffer consequences.. . .. &gt;&gt;<br><br>
  You are partially correct, especially when speaking of WW2, and S.L.A. Marshall wrote of the reluctance of men to fire at the enemy.  There was less of this in Korea.  I beleive it's linked to the culture of &quot;the time.&quot; <br>
  <br>
    The WW2  a generation was bought up &quot;not to kill&quot; and &quot;war is bad&quot;---and &quot;All Quiet...&quot; and all the other great &quot;feel good&quot; movies of the time is a good example of this.<br>
 In ALL the gangster movies, the &quot;killers&quot; ALWAYS paid the price for killing by being killed.  &quot;Live by the sword....&quot;  <br>
Ditto for the radio---and no TV.  <br><br>
     A good part of the VN generation, bought up on WW2 movies, TV and the Cold War do---in my opionion, suffer much less from this.  Today's generation has/will suffer even less.  How many vets from the Gulf War have had these flash-backs etc????<br><br>
   As they say, &quot;never say never or always.&quot;<br><br>
   As a child, I had the opportunity to listen to quite a few Civil War vets [southeren] and I assure you they talked about it a hell of a  lot and if they had any regrets about killing all those Yankees, they hide it very well.  They boasted of it more often then not.  Sang pretty bloody songs also.<br><br>
    I speak from an unusual position.  I was born and raised in the Army, joined two days after High School and went to VN after nine years of professional training.  While killing was never a &quot;casual&quot; affair for me,  &quot;destroying the enemy&quot; was part of my profession and it didn't bother me then and doesn't bother me now.<br><br>
    That's the only thing that has bothered me on occassion---not being bothered.  Intelectual not an emotional exercise.<br><br>
    Among my peers, I've found very little of the type of after effects that have received so much publicity.  While I don't deny that many indaviduals have suffered, I also beleive that---based soley on my personal observations, they are in the minority.  Most VN vets returned, and took up a normal and productive life.  <br><br>
   Not very &quot;news worthy&quot; and how many study the non-affected?  It's not news to talk about no problems and in academia,  your chance of being published writting about a non-problem isn't all that good.<br><br>
   There is a school of thought by those who avoided the combat.  -They are desperate to &quot;prove&quot; that they were right and will use any tool that furthers their attempt to justify their avoiding combat at the exspense of their poorer fellow citizens.  To do otherwise would negate a major---and only &quot;meaningful&quot; event in their lives.  <br><br>
Andy
